<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="271" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="6.[151,1436,1780,2023]" pageId="6" pageNumber="271">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,1888,1914]" pageId="6" pageNumber="271">Etymology:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bota-Sierra &amp; Novelo-Gutiérrez" authorityYear="2020" box="[345,465,1888,1914]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Epigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="6" pageNumber="271" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brillantina">
<emphasis box="[345,465,1888,1914]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="271">brillantina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(to be treated as an indeclinable noun) is the word in Spanish for brilliantine, referring to something shiny. It is the name of the forest island protected and preserved by Don Gustavo Campuzano and his family for the last 30 years, which is a refugee to many species of this region’s flora and fauna, including several endemic and threatened 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Fabricius" authorityYear="1793" box="[424,519,1996,2022]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="6" pageNumber="271" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Odonata</taxonomicName>
species and the only location so far known for this new species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="275" pageId="7" pageNumber="272" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,150,213]" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,477,150,177]" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">
Description of 
<typeStatus box="[374,477,151,177]" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">holotype</typeStatus>
</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[491,552,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Head</emphasis>
brown, frons with two yellow greenish stripes separated by a small brown portion on the middle, clypeus with dorsolateral green spots. Occiput with two small diagonal scars (
<figureCitation box="[1243,1320,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1724,1748]" captionTargetBox="[296,1292,237,1673]" captionTargetId="figure-54@7.[296,1292,237,1701]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. Epigomphus brillantina habitus: a, teneral specimen live in the field (photograph by Camilo Flórez); b, male holotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381866" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381866/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Figs. 6</figureCitation>
a–b, 7a).
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381866" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4381866" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381866/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="272" startId="7.[151,250,1724,1748]" targetBox="[296,1292,237,1673]" targetPageId="7">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1436,1724,1785]" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,276,1724,1748]" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">FIGURE 6.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bota-Sierra &amp; Novelo-Gutiérrez" authorityYear="2020" box="[283,525,1725,1749]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Epigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="7" pageNumber="272" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brillantina">
<emphasis box="[283,525,1725,1749]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Epigomphus brillantina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
habitus: a, teneral specimen live in the field (photograph by Camilo Flórez); b, male holotype.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1831,2037]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1436,151,357]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="273" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">
<emphasis box="[199,280,1831,1857]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Thorax</emphasis>
. Brown, but yellow as follows: pronotum except the posterior lobe, a longitudinal line on mesepisternum and a transverse line on its anterior border, second pale antehumeral stripe reduced to a single, small, posterior spot, a longitudinal line on mesepimeron, a stripe on metepisternum which apex converges with the completely yellow metepimeron, antealar crest with yellow spots (
<figureCitation box="[728,806,1939,1966]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1724,1748]" captionTargetBox="[296,1292,237,1673]" captionTargetId="figure-54@7.[296,1292,237,1701]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. Epigomphus brillantina habitus: a, teneral specimen live in the field (photograph by Camilo Flórez); b, male holotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381866" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381866/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Figs. 6</figureCitation>
a–b). Legs brown except distal portion of femora, tibiae, and tarsi which are black. Metafemora approximately 1 ½ the length of mesofemora (
<figureCitation box="[1115,1193,1975,2002]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1724,1748]" captionTargetBox="[296,1292,237,1673]" captionTargetId="figure-54@7.[296,1292,237,1701]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. Epigomphus brillantina habitus: a, teneral specimen live in the field (photograph by Camilo Flórez); b, male holotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381866" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381866/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="272">Figs. 6</figureCitation>
a–b). All femora with external row of spines. Tibiae with long, slender spines on external border, except protibiae with a row of ten scalelike spines on external side. Tarsal claws brown with subapical tooth. 
<emphasis box="[932,1000,151,176]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="273">Wings</emphasis>
. Hyaline, black veins and brown Pt. Pt covering 9 ½ cells in FW, 7 ½ in right and 8 ½ cells in left HW. Left FW with 17 Ax, right FW with 18, FWs with 15 Px; left HW with 14 Ax, right HW with 13 Ax; left HW with 12 Px, right HW with 13 Px; supratriangles, triangles and subtriangles without crossveins. Second reinforced antenodal in FWs 6th, in the right HW the 6th and in the left the 7th (
<figureCitation box="[243,325,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1872,1896]" captionTargetBox="[148,1439,525,1834]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[148,1439,525,1849]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Epigomphus rufus male paratype abdomen: caudal appendages: a, lateral view; c, dorsal view. b, S2 lateral view; d, S2 ventral view. a. h.: anterior hamuli; a. l.: anterior lamina; a. t.: apical tooth; p. h.: posterior hamuli; s1: first segment of vesica spermalis; sa. t.: subapical tooth." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381858" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381858/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="273">Fig. 4a</figureCitation>
). Cubito-anal crossveins in addition to inner side of subtriangle, 
<quantity box="[1048,1091,295,321]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.62" pageId="8" pageNumber="273" unit="in" value="3.0">3 in</quantity>
FWs, 
<quantity box="[1164,1207,295,321]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.08" pageId="8" pageNumber="273" unit="in" value="2.0">2 in</quantity>
HWs. Crossveins in space between sectors of arculus and point of branching of RP on HW 
<quantity box="[944,987,331,357]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.62" pageId="8" pageNumber="273" unit="in" value="3.0">3 in</quantity>
left, 
<quantity box="[1045,1088,331,357]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.016" pageId="8" pageNumber="273" unit="in" value="4.0">4 in</quantity>
right.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381872" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4381872" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381872/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="273" startId="8.[151,250,1913,1937]" targetBox="[201,1387,381,1885]" targetPageId="8">
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1436,1913,2010]" pageId="8" pageNumber="273">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,276,1913,1938]" pageId="8" pageNumber="273">FIGURE 7.</emphasis>
<emphasis box="[283,533,1914,1938]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="273">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bota-Sierra &amp; Novelo-Gutiérrez" authorityYear="2020" box="[283,527,1914,1938]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Epigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="8" pageNumber="273" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brillantina">Epigomphus brillantina</taxonomicName>
:
</emphasis>
male paratype dorsal view of head; male holotype: b, lateral view of S2; c, ventral view of S2. a. h.: anterior hamuli; a. l.: anterior lamina; cor: cornua; hrn: horns; l. l. p.: lateral lobe slender projection; p. h.: posterior hamuli; prep: prepuce; s1: first segment of vesica spermalis; s3: third segment of vesica spermalis.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381874" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4381874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381874/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="274" startId="9.[151,250,1573,1597]" targetBox="[156,1426,181,1549]" targetPageId="9">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1573,1669]" pageId="9" pageNumber="274">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,277,1573,1597]" pageId="9" pageNumber="274">FIGURE 8.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bota-Sierra &amp; Novelo-Gutiérrez" authorityYear="2020" box="[286,529,1573,1597]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Epigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="9" pageNumber="274" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brillantina">
<emphasis box="[286,529,1573,1597]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="274">Epigomphus brillantina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
male paratype S10 and caudal appendages: a, dorsal view; b ventral view; c, posterior view; d, lateral view. ap: apical process; da. e. p.: dorsoapical external process; da. i. p.: dorsoapical internal process; m. p.: medial process; s. d.: small denticles.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1715,2030]" lastBlockId="10.[151,1437,151,1185]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="275" pageId="9" pageNumber="274">
<emphasis box="[199,305,1715,1741]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="274">Abdomen</emphasis>
. Club-like, becoming thinner on S3 and widening again on S8, S10 is the widest segment (
<figureCitation box="[1303,1379,1715,1742]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1724,1748]" captionTargetBox="[296,1292,237,1673]" captionTargetId="figure-54@7.[296,1292,237,1701]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. Epigomphus brillantina habitus: a, teneral specimen live in the field (photograph by Camilo Flórez); b, male holotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381866" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381866/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="274">Figs. 6</figureCitation>
a–b). Dark brown but S1 yellow except posterodorsal portion, S2 auricles and lateroventral portion yellow, S3 with an anterolateral yellow spot and a thin yellow posterolateral line, S4–6 with anterior yellow rings, S7 anterior ¾ yellow, S8 ventrolateral margin yellow (
<figureCitation box="[562,638,1823,1850]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1724,1748]" captionTargetBox="[296,1292,237,1673]" captionTargetId="figure-54@7.[296,1292,237,1701]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 6. Epigomphus brillantina habitus: a, teneral specimen live in the field (photograph by Camilo Flórez); b, male holotype." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381866" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381866/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="274">Figs. 6</figureCitation>
a–b). Auricles rounded and dorsally swollen with a posterobasal process bearing rows of three black teeth directed ventrally (
<figureCitation box="[760,838,1859,1886]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1913,1937]" captionTargetBox="[201,1387,381,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-153@8.[201,1387,381,1889]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 7. Epigomphus brillantina: male paratype dorsal view of head; male holotype: b, lateral view of S2; c, ventral view of S2. a. h.: anterior hamuli; a. l.: anterior lamina; cor: cornua; hrn: horns; l. l. p.: lateral lobe slender projection; p. h.: posterior hamuli; prep: prepuce; s1: first segment of vesica spermalis; s3: third segment of vesica spermalis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381872" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381872/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="274">Fig 7c</figureCitation>
). Components of genital fossa dark brown, anterior lamina posterior border sinuose in ventral view with a medial concavity (
<figureCitation box="[990,1065,1895,1922]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1913,1937]" captionTargetBox="[201,1387,381,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-153@8.[201,1387,381,1889]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 7. Epigomphus brillantina: male paratype dorsal view of head; male holotype: b, lateral view of S2; c, ventral view of S2. a. h.: anterior hamuli; a. l.: anterior lamina; cor: cornua; hrn: horns; l. l. p.: lateral lobe slender projection; p. h.: posterior hamuli; prep: prepuce; s1: first segment of vesica spermalis; s3: third segment of vesica spermalis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381872" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381872/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="274">Fig 7c</figureCitation>
); anterior hamuli petiolate, widening towards apical portion, ending in a rounded point (
<figureCitation box="[802,876,1931,1958]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1913,1937]" captionTargetBox="[201,1387,381,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-153@8.[201,1387,381,1889]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 7. Epigomphus brillantina: male paratype dorsal view of head; male holotype: b, lateral view of S2; c, ventral view of S2. a. h.: anterior hamuli; a. l.: anterior lamina; cor: cornua; hrn: horns; l. l. p.: lateral lobe slender projection; p. h.: posterior hamuli; prep: prepuce; s1: first segment of vesica spermalis; s3: third segment of vesica spermalis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381872" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381872/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="274">Fig 7c</figureCitation>
); posterior hamuli long, approximately twice the length of anterior hamuli, slightly curved backwards in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[961,1038,1967,1994]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1913,1937]" captionTargetBox="[201,1387,381,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-153@8.[201,1387,381,1889]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 7. Epigomphus brillantina: male paratype dorsal view of head; male holotype: b, lateral view of S2; c, ventral view of S2. a. h.: anterior hamuli; a. l.: anterior lamina; cor: cornua; hrn: horns; l. l. p.: lateral lobe slender projection; p. h.: posterior hamuli; prep: prepuce; s1: first segment of vesica spermalis; s3: third segment of vesica spermalis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381872" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381872/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="274">Fig 7b</figureCitation>
), its mesial side covered by black tubercles (
<figureCitation box="[273,350,2003,2030]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1913,1937]" captionTargetBox="[201,1387,381,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-153@8.[201,1387,381,1889]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 7. Epigomphus brillantina: male paratype dorsal view of head; male holotype: b, lateral view of S2; c, ventral view of S2. a. h.: anterior hamuli; a. l.: anterior lamina; cor: cornua; hrn: horns; l. l. p.: lateral lobe slender projection; p. h.: posterior hamuli; prep: prepuce; s1: first segment of vesica spermalis; s3: third segment of vesica spermalis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381872" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381872/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="274">Fig 7c</figureCitation>
). 
<emphasis box="[372,561,2003,2029]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="274">Vesica spermalis</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[578,655,2003,2029]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1913,1937]" captionTargetBox="[201,1387,381,1885]" captionTargetId="figure-153@8.[201,1387,381,1889]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 7. Epigomphus brillantina: male paratype dorsal view of head; male holotype: b, lateral view of S2; c, ventral view of S2. a. h.: anterior hamuli; a. l.: anterior lamina; cor: cornua; hrn: horns; l. l. p.: lateral lobe slender projection; p. h.: posterior hamuli; prep: prepuce; s1: first segment of vesica spermalis; s3: third segment of vesica spermalis." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381872" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381872/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="274">Figs. 7</figureCitation>
b–c, 8a): segment 1 concave in ventral view, in lateral view with a ventroapical rounded process directed distally; segment 3 widening towards its distal portion, two ventro apical horns directed distally; segment 4, prepuce rounded, lateral lobe strongly bulging dorsally, with a slender projection directed posteriorly and parallel to cornua; cornua short. Cercus longer than epiproct and S10 (
<figureCitation box="[1231,1310,223,250]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1573,1597]" captionTargetBox="[156,1426,181,1549]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[156,1430,181,1549]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. Epigomphus brillantina male paratype S10 and caudal appendages: a, dorsal view; b ventral view; c, posterior view; d, lateral view. ap: apical process; da. e. p.: dorsoapical external process; da. i. p.: dorsoapical internal process; m. p.: medial process; s. d.: small denticles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381874/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Figs. 8</figureCitation>
e–f). Cerci concave mesially, in lateral view, with a dorsoapical pointed mesial process which turns downwards (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1573,1597]" captionTargetBox="[156,1426,181,1549]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[156,1430,181,1549]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. Epigomphus brillantina male paratype S10 and caudal appendages: a, dorsal view; b ventral view; c, posterior view; d, lateral view. ap: apical process; da. e. p.: dorsoapical external process; da. i. p.: dorsoapical internal process; m. p.: medial process; s. d.: small denticles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381874/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Figs. 8</figureCitation>
e–f), the ventroapical edge has a series of four small denticles (
<figureCitation box="[906,1003,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1573,1597]" captionTargetBox="[156,1426,181,1549]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[156,1430,181,1549]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. Epigomphus brillantina male paratype S10 and caudal appendages: a, dorsal view; b ventral view; c, posterior view; d, lateral view. ap: apical process; da. e. p.: dorsoapical external process; da. i. p.: dorsoapical internal process; m. p.: medial process; s. d.: small denticles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381874/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Figs. 8c</figureCitation>
, e–f), in posterior and dorsal views a rounded dorsoapical external process is observed (
<figureCitation box="[749,829,331,358]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1573,1597]" captionTargetBox="[156,1426,181,1549]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[156,1430,181,1549]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. Epigomphus brillantina male paratype S10 and caudal appendages: a, dorsal view; b ventral view; c, posterior view; d, lateral view. ap: apical process; da. e. p.: dorsoapical external process; da. i. p.: dorsoapical internal process; m. p.: medial process; s. d.: small denticles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381874/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Figs. 8</figureCitation>
b–c). Epiproct divided in two lateroapical branches (
<figureCitation box="[160,240,367,394]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1573,1597]" captionTargetBox="[156,1426,181,1549]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[156,1430,181,1549]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. Epigomphus brillantina male paratype S10 and caudal appendages: a, dorsal view; b ventral view; c, posterior view; d, lateral view. ap: apical process; da. e. p.: dorsoapical external process; da. i. p.: dorsoapical internal process; m. p.: medial process; s. d.: small denticles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381874/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Figs. 8</figureCitation>
b–d), each of them with a rounded tubercle on tip and an elevated medial process which is easily observed in posterior view (
<figureCitation box="[454,535,403,430]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1573,1597]" captionTargetBox="[156,1426,181,1549]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[156,1430,181,1549]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. Epigomphus brillantina male paratype S10 and caudal appendages: a, dorsal view; b ventral view; c, posterior view; d, lateral view. ap: apical process; da. e. p.: dorsoapical external process; da. i. p.: dorsoapical internal process; m. p.: medial process; s. d.: small denticles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381874/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Figs. 8</figureCitation>
b–c); the lateroapical branches converge in a medial oval notch which is not easily observed in dorsal view since it is invaginated under the lateroapical processes of epiproct (
<figureCitation box="[1249,1371,439,466]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1573,1597]" captionTargetBox="[156,1426,181,1549]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[156,1430,181,1549]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. Epigomphus brillantina male paratype S10 and caudal appendages: a, dorsal view; b ventral view; c, posterior view; d, lateral view. ap: apical process; da. e. p.: dorsoapical external process; da. i. p.: dorsoapical internal process; m. p.: medial process; s. d.: small denticles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381874/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Figs. 8b, d</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1185]" box="[199,803,474,501]" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,374,475,501]" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Measurements</emphasis>
(mm): TL 57, Ab 44, FW 37, HW 35.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1185]" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,433,510,537]" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">
<typeStatus box="[199,308,511,537]" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Paratype</typeStatus>
variation:
</emphasis>
Pt. Pt covering 8 cells in FW, 9 ½ HW. Ax in FW 16–17, Px in FW 12; Ax, in HW 13, Px in HW 13. Second reinforced antenodal in FWs 6–7th; (
<figureCitation box="[767,848,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1872,1896]" captionTargetBox="[148,1439,525,1834]" captionTargetId="figure-190@4.[148,1439,525,1849]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Epigomphus rufus male paratype abdomen: caudal appendages: a, lateral view; c, dorsal view. b, S2 lateral view; d, S2 ventral view. a. h.: anterior hamuli; a. l.: anterior lamina; a. t.: apical tooth; p. h.: posterior hamuli; s1: first segment of vesica spermalis; sa. t.: subapical tooth." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381858" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381858/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Fig. 4a</figureCitation>
). Two cubito-anal crossveins in addition to inner side of subtriangle in FW. Five crossveins in space between sectors of arculus and point of branching of RP on HW.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1185]" box="[199,803,618,645]" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,374,619,645]" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Measurements</emphasis>
(mm): TL 56, Ab 43, FW 36, HW 34.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="10" pageNumber="275" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1437,151,1185]" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,654,680]" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bota-Sierra &amp; Novelo-Gutiérrez" authorityYear="2020" box="[330,598,655,681]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Epigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brillantina">
<emphasis box="[330,598,655,681]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Epigomphus brillantina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shares with a group of 16 species, including most of the South American and some Central American species, its second pale antehumeral stripe reduced to a single small posterior spot (
<tableCitation box="[159,243,727,753]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="6.[151,239,440,464]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="TABLE 1. Epigomphus species with second pale antehumeral stripe reduced to a single small posterior spot, their distribution, and male cercus length compared with S10 length." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF7666642319FF8AFF3D63FDFC91BFE9" pageId="10" pageNumber="275" tableUuid="DF7666642319FF8AFF3D63FDFC91BFE9">Table 1</tableCitation>
). Among them, the males of eleven species share with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bota-Sierra &amp; Novelo-Gutiérrez" authorityYear="2020" box="[867,1019,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Epigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brillantina">
<emphasis box="[867,1019,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">E. brillantina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
cercus length longer than S10 (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1573,1597]" captionTargetBox="[156,1426,181,1549]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[156,1430,181,1549]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. Epigomphus brillantina male paratype S10 and caudal appendages: a, dorsal view; b ventral view; c, posterior view; d, lateral view. ap: apical process; da. e. p.: dorsoapical external process; da. i. p.: dorsoapical internal process; m. p.: medial process; s. d.: small denticles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381874/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Figs. 8</figureCitation>
e–f). Within this group, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bota-Sierra &amp; Novelo-Gutiérrez" authorityYear="2020" box="[437,588,763,789]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Epigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brillantina">
<emphasis box="[437,588,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">E. brillantina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Calvert" authorityYear="1903" box="[643,798,763,789]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Epigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadracies">
<emphasis box="[643,798,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">E. quadracies</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the only two species that share cercus with a pointed dorsoapical process curved downward easily observed in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[949,1025,799,826]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1573,1597]" captionTargetBox="[156,1426,181,1549]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[156,1430,181,1549]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. Epigomphus brillantina male paratype S10 and caudal appendages: a, dorsal view; b ventral view; c, posterior view; d, lateral view. ap: apical process; da. e. p.: dorsoapical external process; da. i. p.: dorsoapical internal process; m. p.: medial process; s. d.: small denticles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381874/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Figs. 8</figureCitation>
e–f), but 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bota-Sierra &amp; Novelo-Gutiérrez" authorityYear="2020" box="[1131,1283,799,825]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Epigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brillantina">
<emphasis box="[1131,1283,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">E. brillantina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Calvert" authorityYear="1903" box="[371,527,835,861]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Epigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadracies">
<emphasis box="[371,527,835,861]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">E. quadracies</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the shape of its epiproct which has a rounded apical tubercle on each lateroapical process while in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Calvert" authorityYear="1903" box="[418,575,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Epigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadracies">
<emphasis box="[418,575,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">E. quadracies</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
two apical points are observed (
<bibRefCitation author="Calvert, P. P." box="[944,1095,871,897]" pageId="10" pageNumber="275" pagination="323 - 354" refId="ref5110" refString="Calvert, P. P. (1920) The Costa Rican species of Epigomphus and their mutual mating adaptations (Odonata). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 46, 323 - 354." type="journal article" year="1920">Calvert 1920</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kennedy, C. H." box="[1108,1274,871,898]" pageId="10" pageNumber="275" pagination="662 - 666" refId="ref5390" refString="Kennedy, C. H. (1946) Epigomphus subquadrices, a New Dragonfly (Odonata: Gomphidae) from Panama, with notes on E. quadrices and Eugomphus N. Subgen. Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 39, 662 - 666. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / aesa / 39.4.662" type="journal article" year="1946">Kennedy 1946</bibRefCitation>
) (
<figureCitation box="[1299,1376,871,898]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1573,1597]" captionTargetBox="[156,1426,181,1549]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[156,1430,181,1549]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. Epigomphus brillantina male paratype S10 and caudal appendages: a, dorsal view; b ventral view; c, posterior view; d, lateral view. ap: apical process; da. e. p.: dorsoapical external process; da. i. p.: dorsoapical internal process; m. p.: medial process; s. d.: small denticles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381874/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Figs. 8</figureCitation>
b–d). Also, the median portion of the posterior border of epiproct has a quadrangular notch in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Calvert" authorityYear="1903" box="[1177,1335,907,933]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Epigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadracies">
<emphasis box="[1177,1335,907,933]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">E. quadracies</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Calvert, P. P." pageId="10" pageNumber="275" pagination="323 - 354" refId="ref5110" refString="Calvert, P. P. (1920) The Costa Rican species of Epigomphus and their mutual mating adaptations (Odonata). Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 46, 323 - 354." type="journal article" year="1920">Calvert 1920</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Kennedy, C. H." box="[222,386,943,970]" pageId="10" pageNumber="275" pagination="662 - 666" refId="ref5390" refString="Kennedy, C. H. (1946) Epigomphus subquadrices, a New Dragonfly (Odonata: Gomphidae) from Panama, with notes on E. quadrices and Eugomphus N. Subgen. Annals of the Entomological Society of America, 39, 662 - 666. https: // doi. org / 10.1093 / aesa / 39.4.662" type="journal article" year="1946">Kennedy 1946</bibRefCitation>
) that can be observed both in ventral and dorsal view, while in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bota-Sierra &amp; Novelo-Gutiérrez" authorityYear="2020" box="[1090,1241,943,969]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Epigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brillantina">
<emphasis box="[1090,1241,943,969]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">E. brillantina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
this notch is oval and is not easily observed in dorsal view since it is invaginated under the lateroapical processes of epiproct (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1573,1597]" captionTargetBox="[156,1426,181,1549]" captionTargetId="figure-17@9.[156,1430,181,1549]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 8. Epigomphus brillantina male paratype S10 and caudal appendages: a, dorsal view; b ventral view; c, posterior view; d, lateral view. ap: apical process; da. e. p.: dorsoapical external process; da. i. p.: dorsoapical internal process; m. p.: medial process; s. d.: small denticles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4381874" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4381874/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">Figs. 8</figureCitation>
b–d). Furthermore, the dorsal slender projection of the vesica spermalis fourth segment is longer in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bota-Sierra &amp; Novelo-Gutiérrez" authorityYear="2020" box="[1285,1436,1015,1041]" class="Insecta" family="Gomphidae" genus="Epigomphus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Odonata" pageId="10" pageNumber="275" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brillantina">
<emphasis box="[1285,1436,1015,1041]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="275">E. brillantina</emphasis>
